[1] Cholera - Philippines
Date: Mon 29 Nov 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Sun Star [edited]
<http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/bac/2004/11/29/news/guv.cholera.cases.in.negocc.not.alarming.html>

Governor says cholera cases in Negros Occidental not alarming
-----------------------------------------------
Governor Joseph Maranon said the reported suspected cholera cases in Negros
Occidental are not alarming, as he advised residents to clean their
surroundings. He said that the report released by the Provincial Health
Office (PHO) on Fri 26 Nov 2004, of about 86 cases in the province,
including Bacolod City, will still be subject to laboratory examination.
The governor added that the report was only advice for residents to check
on their drinking water and to clean their surroundings. "The suspected
cases remain manageable and not alarming," said Maranon.
Records earlier showed that suspected cases of cholera in the province
reached 86, with 3 deaths, from 14 to 20 Nov 2004. Kabankalan City had the
largest number of cases, with 40 in 16 barangays, followed by Bacolod City
with 23, Ilog with 9, Cauayan with 5, Bago City and Himamaylan City with 2
each, and Victorias City and E B Magalona with one each.
Dr Luisa Efren of the PHO ordered the examination of all possible sources
of drinking water and pipes, specifically in Kabankalan. She advised the
city municipal health offices to conduct massive information dissemination
on environmental sanitation, boiling, and chlorination of drinking water
and personal hygiene practices.
[byline: Avelyn Z Agudon]
******
[2] Gastroenteritis - Philippines
Date: Sun 28 Nov 2004
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@ntlworld.com>
Source: The Philippine Star [edited]
<http://www.philstar.com/philstar/News200411289903.htm>

Gastroenteritis outbreak in Cebu: 4 dead, 100 hospitalized
----------------------------------------------------------
4 people died, while over 100 were admitted to hospital, in 2 southern Cebu
towns, due to gastroenteritis caused by a contaminated water supply. Two
men, aged 40 and 80 years, both from Barangay Malabagon, Moalboal town,
died last Thu 25 Nov 2004 from acute gastroenteritis. 2 others reportedly
died in Pinamungajan town because of acute infectious diarrhea. 25 more
have been admitted to the town's district hospital since 1 Nov 2004.
In Moalboal, municipal health officer Cesar Mahinay said he had 100
patients in his clinic as of Fri 26 Nov 2004, all complaining of
stomachache and diarrhea. 45 others have been confined at the Badian
District Hospital since Tue 23 Nov 2004. Mahinay said 25 others were
brought to the Barili District Hospital, since the Badian District Hospital
only has 25 beds.
Provincial health officer Cristina Giango confirmed the outbreak of acute
gastroenteritis in Moalboal. She said water samples taken from Moalboal
tested positive for coliforms. But, she said they are still conducting
confirmatory tests to determine the type of bacteria that contaminated the
town's water supply.
Juanito Zuasola, regional epidemiologist of the Department of Health,
corroborated Giango's pronouncement, saying the cases have swelled in just
a short span of time. Zuasola, however, said they only learned about the
outbreak last Fri 25 Nov 2004, because local officials failed to report the
initial cases to them.
But Giango traced the source of the contamination to a leaking pipe of the
Moalboal Water District. A day after the pipes were repaired, on Mon 22 Nov
2004, the 1st case of gastroenteritis was reported, and the ailment
subsequently spread to at least 5 barangays, namely Malabagon, Poblacion
East, Poblacion West, Tamonoy, and Basdacu.
[byline: Fred Languido and Jasmin Uy]
--
Pablo Nart
<p.nart@ntlworld.com>
[The death of a 40 year old, and 4 deaths overall, suggest the possibility
of cholera. - Mod.LL]
