[4] Gastroenteritis - Indonesia
Date: Mon 22 Nov 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AsiaNews.it [edited]
<http://www.asianews.it/view.php?l=en&art=1955>

10 children die in diarrhea outbreak in East Java
-------------------------------------------------
At least 10 children died and another 1300 were admitted to hospital after
an acute diarrhea outbreak hit East Java in the last week [3rd week of Nov
2004]. The Health Office in the Central Java province of Khrisnajaya
released a statement saying that more than 600 villages across the province
are vulnerable to the disease. "We are easily becoming prone to the
disease," health officials said, "but we have prepared things to stop it
from spreading".
The worst cases were reported in Makassar and Surabaya, respectively the
provincial capitals of South Sulawesi and East Java. Local heath
authorities said that, in Makassar, more than 2000 diarrhea patients are
suffering from belly aches and vomiting. Other cases have been reported in
Solok, West Sumatra Province: 332 people had to be hospitalized, another 10
died.
Siti Fadillah Supeni, Indonesia's Health Minister, expressed her concern
about delays in treatment that resulted in many patients dying of
dehydration. Cholera might be the cause of the outbreak, possibly being
related to the rush to prepare food for the Idul Fitri celebration that
marked the end of Ramadan, Islam's holy month of fasting.
[Again, cholera may be responsible for some, if not many, of these cases. -
Mod.LL]
