[5] Cholera - Nigeria
Date: Thu 25 Nov 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: BusinessinAfrica.net [edited]
<http://www.businessinafrica.net/news/393432.htm>

Cholera cases rise in Kano
-------------------------
Cholera cases in Kano rose to nearly 1000 yesterday [Wed 24 Nov 2004] from
642 last week, state health commissioner Sanda Mohammed has said. "A total
of 962 people have been hospitalized at the Infectious Diseases Hospital in
Kano since the outbreak 2 weeks ago, out of which, 47 have died," he said,
one more than the 46 reported on Mon 22 Nov 2004.
He said the disease had now affected 20 local government areas, up from 14
previously, despite measures taken by health authorities to combat it. Last
week [3rd week of Nov 2004], it was reported that 42 people had died when
the deadly waterborne infection erupted in the crowded city. Mohammed said
that, last week, the disease had broken out because Muslim worshippers had
been in a rush to prepare fruit and vegetables for a feast to mark the end
of Ramadan and had not washed them properly.
The disease later spread to neighboring Jigawa State, claiming 4 lives
among 104 cases, senior health official Mustapha Muhammed said. Cholera is
generally contracted from polluted water supplies. It causes vomiting and
severe diarrhea that can result in rapid dehydration and eventual death if
not treated.
